-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- HEBREWS CHAPTER 10 — The Once-for-All Sacrifice and the Fourth Warning
-- 39 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 10,
  'Hebrews 10 concludes the doctrinal argument (vv.1-18) and pivots to application (vv.19-39). The chapter opens by reaffirming that the law''s sacrifices were shadows that ''can never with those sacrifices which they offered year by year continually make the comers thereunto perfect'' (v.1). Annual repetition proves inadequacy: ''in those sacrifices there is a remembrance again made of sins every year'' (v.3), ''for it is not possible that the blood of bulls and of goats should take away sins'' (v.4). Quoting Psalm 40:6-8, the author shows Christ''s obedient self-offering replacing animal sacrifice: ''a body hast thou prepared me … Lo, I come to do thy will, O God'' (vv.5-7). ''By the which will we are sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all'' (v.10). While Levitical priests stand daily offering repeatedly, Christ ''after he had offered one sacrifice for sins for ever, sat down on the right hand of God'' (v.12). ''For by one offering he hath perfected for ever them that are sanctified'' (v.14). The Holy Spirit witnesses through Jeremiah 31: ''their sins and iniquities will I remember no more. Now where remission of these is, there is no more offering for sin'' (vv.17-18). The application begins: ''Having therefore, brethren, boldness to enter into the holiest by the blood of Jesus, by a new and living way … let us draw near … let us hold fast … let us consider one another'' (vv.19-25). The fourth warning follows: ''if we sin wilfully after that we have received the knowledge of the truth, there remaineth no more sacrifice for sins'' (v.26). ''It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God'' (v.31). The chapter ends with encouragement: remember your former endurance (vv.32-34), do not ''cast away your confidence'' (v.35), for ''ye have need of patience'' (v.36), and ''the just shall live by faith'' (v.38).',
  'The Perfected Sacrifice, the New and Living Way, and the Fourth Warning',
  'ἅπαξ / ἐφάπαξ (hapax / ephapax)',
  'Once / once for all — the decisive words of Hebrews'' sacrificial theology. Hapax (once) and its intensified form ephapax (once for all) express the unrepeatable nature of Christ''s sacrifice. In 10:10 ''once for all'' (ephapax) describes the offering of Christ''s body; in 10:12 ''one sacrifice for sins for ever'' captures the permanent sufficiency. The word stands against all repetition, all supplementation, all re-offering. Christ''s sacrifice is complete, final, and all-sufficient.',
  '["The Shadow Cannot Perfect (vv.1-4): For the law having a shadow of good things to come and not the very image of the things can never with those sacrifices which they offered year by year continually make the comers thereunto perfect; for then would they not have ceased to be offered because that the worshippers once purged should have had no more conscience of sins; but in those sacrifices there is a remembrance again made of sins every year; for it is not possible that the blood of bulls and of goats should take away sins","Christ''s Obedient Self-Offering (vv.5-10): Wherefore when he cometh into the world he saith Sacrifice and offering thou wouldest not but a body hast thou prepared me; in burnt offerings and sacrifices for sin thou hast had no pleasure; then said I Lo I come in the volume of the book it is written of me to do thy will O God; above when he said Sacrifice and offering and burnt offerings and offering for sin thou wouldest not neither hadst pleasure therein which are offered by the law; then said he Lo I come to do thy will O God he taketh away the first that he may establish the second; by the which will we are sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all","One Sacrifice: Sat Down Forever (vv.11-18): And every priest standeth daily ministering and offering oftentimes the same sacrifices which can never take away sins; but this man after he had offered one sacrifice for sins for ever sat down on the right hand of God; from henceforth expecting till his enemies be made his footstool; for by one offering he hath perfected for ever them that are sanctified; whereof the Holy Ghost also is a witness to us for after that he had said before This is the covenant that I will make with them after those days saith the Lord I will put my laws into their hearts and in their minds will I write them; and their sins and iniquities will I remember no more; now where remission of these is there is no more offering for sin","The New and Living Way: Three Exhortations (vv.19-25): Having therefore brethren boldness to enter into the holiest by the blood of Jesus by a new and living way which he hath consecrated for us through the veil that is to say his flesh; and having an high priest over the house of God; let us draw near with a true heart in full assurance of faith having our hearts sprinkled from an evil conscience and our bodies washed with pure water; let us hold fast the profession of our faith without wavering for he is faithful that promised; and let us consider one another to provoke unto love and to good works; not forsaking the assembling of ourselves together as the manner of some is but exhorting one another and so much the more as ye see the day approaching","The Fourth Warning: Wilful Sin (vv.26-31): For if we sin wilfully after that we have received the knowledge of the truth there remaineth no more sacrifice for sins but a certain fearful looking for of judgment and fiery indignation which shall devour the adversaries; he that despised Moses law died without mercy under two or three witnesses; of how much sorer punishment suppose ye shall he be thought worthy who hath trodden under foot the Son of God and hath counted the blood of the covenant wherewith he was sanctified an unholy thing and hath done despite unto the Spirit of grace; for we know him that hath said Vengeance belongeth unto me I will recompense saith the Lord and again The Lord shall judge his people; it is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God","Call to Endurance and Faith (vv.32-39): But call to remembrance the former days in which after ye were illuminated ye endured a great fight of afflictions; partly whilst ye were made a gazingstock both by reproaches and afflictions and partly whilst ye became companions of them that were so used; for ye had compassion of me in my bonds and took joyfully the spoiling of your goods knowing in yourselves that ye have in heaven a better and an enduring substance; cast not away therefore your confidence which hath great recompence of reward; for ye have need of patience that after ye have done the will of God ye might receive the promise; for yet a little while and he that shall come will come and will not tarry; now the just shall live by faith but if any man draw back my soul shall have no pleasure in him; but we are not of them who draw back unto perdition but of them that believe to the saving of the soul"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews';

-- Step 2: Insert all 39 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'For the law having a shadow of good things to come, and not the very image of the things, can never with those sacrifices which they offered year by year continually make the comers thereunto perfect.',
   'σκιὰν γὰρ ἔχων ὁ νόμος τῶν μελλόντων ἀγαθῶν οὐκ αὐτὴν τὴν εἰκόνα τῶν πραγμάτων κατ᾽ ἐνιαυτὸν ταῖς αὐταῖς θυσίαις ἃς προσφέρουσιν εἰς τὸ διηνεκὲς οὐδέποτε δύναται τοὺς προσερχομένους τελειῶσαι',
   'skian gar echōn ho nomos tōn mellontōn agathōn ouk autēn tēn eikona tōn pragmatōn kat eniauton tais autais thysiais has prospherousin eis to diēnekes oudepote dynatai tous proserchomenous teleiōsai',
   '''A shadow'' (skian — a silhouette, not the substance). ''Not the very image'' (ouk autēn tēn eikona — not the exact representation; eikōn means likeness, image — the substance itself). The law provides a shadow; Christ is the image — the reality. ''Year by year continually'' (kat eniauton eis to diēnekes — annually, perpetually). ''Can never'' (oudepote dynatai — is never able, not at any time). ''Make perfect'' (teleiōsai — bring to completion). The annual repetition proves the law''s sacrifices are permanently insufficient — they can never achieve what they repeatedly attempt.',
   'The shadow/image distinction is fundamental: the old covenant was the shadow; Christ is the reality. Shadows are valuable — they reveal shape and direction — but they have no substance. The law''s sacrifices pointed to Christ but could not accomplish what only He could do.'),
  (2, 'For then would they not have ceased to be offered? because that the worshippers once purged should have had no more conscience of sins.',
   'ἐπεὶ οὐκ ἂν ἐπαύσαντο προσφερόμεναι διὰ τὸ μηδεμίαν ἔχειν ἔτι συνείδησιν ἁμαρτιῶν τοὺς λατρεύοντας ἅπαξ κεκαθαρμένους',
   'epei ouk an epausanto prospheromenai dia to mēdemian echein eti syneidēsin hamartiōn tous latreuontas hapax kekatharmenous',
   'The logic is irrefutable: if the sacrifices actually worked (removed sin permanently), they would have stopped being offered. The worshippers, ''once purged'' (hapax kekatharmenous — once having been cleansed), would ''have no more conscience of sins'' — no lingering guilt, no annual reminder. But the sacrifices continued year after year, proving they never fully solved the problem.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'But in those sacrifices there is a remembrance again made of sins every year.',
   'ἀλλ᾽ ἐν αὐταῖς ἀνάμνησις ἁμαρτιῶν κατ᾽ ἐνιαυτόν',
   'all en autais anamnēsis hamartiōn kat eniauton',
   '''Remembrance'' (anamnēsis — a recalling, a bringing to mind again). Instead of removing the consciousness of sin, the annual Day of Atonement actually reinforced it — it reminded the worshippers every year that their sins had not been fully dealt with. The same word anamnēsis appears in Luke 22:19 (''this do in remembrance of me'') — but the Lord''s Supper remembers a completed sacrifice, while the Day of Atonement remembered an incomplete one.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'For it is not possible that the blood of bulls and of goats should take away sins.',
   'ἀδύνατον γὰρ αἷμα ταύρων καὶ τράγων ἀφαιρεῖν ἁμαρτίας',
   'adynaton gar haima taurōn kai tragōn aphairein hamartias',
   '''Not possible'' (adynaton — impossible; the same word from 6:4,18). ''Take away'' (aphairein — to remove, to carry off, to strip away). Animal blood is fundamentally incapable of removing human sin. An animal cannot substitute for a human being — it lacks moral agency, personal relationship with God, and voluntary consent. The entire sacrificial system was a divinely appointed illustration, not a solution. Only a human being could substitute for human beings — and only a sinless one could bear others'' sins without being consumed by His own.',
   'This verse states the absolute theological impossibility of animal atonement. Animal blood could never actually remove sin — it was always a temporary covering, a type, a pointer to the reality that only Christ''s blood could achieve. The entire OT sacrificial system was preparatory and illustrative, never ultimate.'),
  (5, 'Wherefore when he cometh into the world, he saith, Sacrifice and offering thou wouldest not, but a body hast thou prepared me:',
   'διὸ εἰσερχόμενος εἰς τὸν κόσμον λέγει θυσίαν καὶ προσφορὰν οὐκ ἠθέλησας σῶμα δὲ κατηρτίσω μοι',
   'dio eiserchomenos eis ton kosmon legei thysian kai prosphoran ouk ēthelēsas sōma de katērtisō moi',
   'Quoting Psalm 40:6-8 (LXX). ''When he cometh into the world'' — the incarnation itself is a speech act. ''Sacrifice and offering thou wouldest not'' (ouk ēthelēsas — you did not desire/delight in). ''A body hast thou prepared me'' (sōma katērtisō moi — you prepared/fashioned a body for me). The Hebrew text has ''mine ears hast thou opened'' (dug/pierced); the LXX renders ''a body hast thou prepared'' — the whole body for the whole person, made ready for obedient self-offering. God did not ultimately want animal sacrifices; He wanted the obedient self-giving of His Son — which required a human body.',
   'The preparation of a body for the Son is the incarnation: God fashioned a human body for Christ so He could offer that body as the perfect sacrifice (v.10). The shift from ''sacrifice and offering'' (external, animal) to ''a body … prepared'' (incarnate, personal) marks the transition from type to antitype, from shadow to substance.'),
  (6, 'In burnt offerings and sacrifices for sin thou hast had no pleasure.',
   'ὁλοκαυτώματα καὶ περὶ ἁμαρτίας οὐκ εὐδόκησας',
   'holokautōmata kai peri hamartias ouk eudokēsas',
   '''Burnt offerings'' (holokautōmata — whole burnt offerings, completely consumed by fire). ''Sacrifices for sin'' (peri hamartias — concerning sin, sin offerings). ''No pleasure'' (ouk eudokēsas — you did not take delight, you were not well-pleased). God ordained the sacrificial system but was never ultimately satisfied by it — it was always a temporary measure, always pointing to something better. The prophets repeatedly expressed God''s dissatisfaction with mere ritual divorced from heart-obedience (1 Sam 15:22; Isa 1:11-17; Mic 6:6-8).',
   NULL),
  (7, 'Then said I, Lo, I come (in the volume of the book it is written of me,) to do thy will, O God.',
   'τότε εἶπον ἰδοὺ ἥκω ἐν κεφαλίδι βιβλίου γέγραπται περὶ ἐμοῦ τοῦ ποιῆσαι ὁ θεὸς τὸ θέλημά σου',
   'tote eipon idou hēkō en kephalidi bibliou gegraptai peri emou tou poiēsai ho theos to thelēma sou',
   '''Lo, I come'' (idou hēkō — behold, I have come; present tense: I am here). ''In the volume of the book it is written of me'' (en kephalidi bibliou gegraptai peri emou — in the scroll of the book it stands written concerning me). All of Scripture testifies to Christ (Luke 24:27; John 5:39). ''To do thy will, O God'' (tou poiēsai to thelēma sou — to accomplish your will). This is the Son''s response to the Father''s dissatisfaction with animal sacrifices: ''I have come to do your will'' — to offer the one sacrifice that perfectly satisfies God''s justice and love.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'Above when he said, Sacrifice and offering and burnt offerings and offering for sin thou wouldest not, neither hadst pleasure therein; which are offered by the law;',
   'ἀνώτερον λέγων θυσίαν καὶ προσφορὰν καὶ ὁλοκαυτώματα καὶ περὶ ἁμαρτίας οὐκ ἠθέλησας οὐδὲ εὐδόκησας αἵτινες κατὰ τὸν νόμον προσφέρονται',
   'anōteron legōn thysian kai prosphoran kai holokautōmata kai peri hamartias ouk ēthelēsas oude eudokēsas haitines kata ton nomon prospherontai',
   'The author draws out the interpretive significance of Psalm 40. Four categories of offering are listed: sacrifice (thysian), offering (prosphoran), burnt offerings (holokautōmata), sin offerings (peri hamartias) — comprehensively covering the entire Levitical sacrificial system. God ''did not desire'' and ''had no pleasure'' in any of them. ''Which are offered by the law'' — these are not unauthorized offerings but the very sacrifices God''s own law prescribed. Yet even God''s own prescribed system did not ultimately please Him — because it was always intended to be temporary.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'Then said he, Lo, I come to do thy will, O God. He taketh away the first, that he may establish the second.',
   'τότε εἴρηκεν ἰδοὺ ἥκω τοῦ ποιῆσαι τὸ θέλημά σου ἀναιρεῖ τὸ πρῶτον ἵνα τὸ δεύτερον στήσῃ',
   'tote eirēken idou hēkō tou poiēsai to thelēma sou anairei to prōton hina to deuteron stēsē',
   '''He taketh away the first'' (anairei to prōton — He removes, abolishes the first). ''That he may establish the second'' (hina to deuteron stēsē — so that He may set up, confirm the second). The ''first'' is the entire sacrificial system of the old covenant; the ''second'' is Christ''s obedient self-offering. The transition is not gradual but decisive: the first is removed so the second can stand. Christ''s coming does not reform the old system but replaces it.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'By the which will we are sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.',
   'ἐν ᾧ θελήματι ἡγιασμένοι ἐσμὲν διὰ τῆς προσφορᾶς τοῦ σώματος τοῦ Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ ἐφάπαξ',
   'en hō thelēmati hēgiasmenoi esmen dia tēs prosphoras tou sōmatos tou Iēsou Christou ephapax',
   '''By the which will'' (en hō thelēmati — by this will, God''s will that Christ came to do). ''We are sanctified'' (hēgiasmenoi esmen — we have been and remain sanctified; perfect participle: a completed action with ongoing results). ''Through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ'' (dia tēs prosphoras tou sōmatos — through the offering of the body). ''Once for all'' (ephapax — once and never again). The sanctification of believers is accomplished by a single, unrepeatable act: the offering of Christ''s body. This sanctification is not a process here but a definitive, completed reality — believers have been set apart by Christ''s sacrifice.',
   'This verse declares that believers are definitively sanctified — set apart for God — through Christ''s once-for-all bodily sacrifice. The perfect tense ''we have been sanctified'' (hēgiasmenoi esmen) emphasizes the completed, permanent nature of this consecration. While experiential sanctification is ongoing, positional sanctification was accomplished at the cross.'),
  (11, 'And every priest standeth daily ministering and offering oftentimes the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins:',
   'καὶ πᾶς μὲν ἱερεὺς ἕστηκεν καθ᾽ ἡμέραν λειτουργῶν καὶ τὰς αὐτὰς πολλάκις προσφέρων θυσίας αἵτινες οὐδέποτε δύνανται περιελεῖν ἁμαρτίας',
   'kai pas men hiereus hestēken kath hēmeran leitourgōn kai tas autas pollakis prospherōn thysias haitines oudepote dynantai perielein hamartias',
   '''Every priest standeth'' (hestēken — stands; the priest never sits because his work is never finished). ''Daily'' (kath hēmeran). ''Oftentimes'' (pollakis — frequently, repeatedly). ''The same sacrifices'' (tas autas thysias — the identical sacrifices, over and over). ''Never'' (oudepote — at no time ever). ''Take away'' (perielein — to strip off, to remove completely). Standing, daily, repeatedly, same, never — five words that describe the futility of the old system. The standing priest is the perfect contrast to the seated Christ (v.12).',
   NULL),
  (12, 'But this man, after he had offered one sacrifice for sins for ever, sat down on the right hand of God;',
   'αὐτὸς δὲ μίαν ὑπὲρ ἁμαρτιῶν προσενέγκας θυσίαν εἰς τὸ διηνεκὲς ἐκάθισεν ἐν δεξιᾷ τοῦ θεοῦ',
   'autos de mian hyper hamartiōn prosenenkas thysian eis to diēnekes ekathisen en dexia tou theou',
   '''One sacrifice'' (mian thysian — a single offering). ''For ever'' (eis to diēnekes — for perpetuity, permanently; modifies either the sacrifice or the sitting — both are true). ''Sat down'' (ekathisen — He sat down). The contrast with v.11 is devastating: the Levitical priest stands (unfinished work) daily (constant repetition) offering the same sacrifices (ineffective); Christ offered one sacrifice (sufficient), sat down (finished work), forever (permanent effect). The seated Christ is the ultimate proof that atonement is complete.',
   'The session of Christ — sitting down at God''s right hand — is the declaration that the work of atonement is finished. In the tabernacle there was no chair — the priest never sat because the work was never done. Christ sat down because there is nothing more to do. This single image demolishes every system that requires ongoing or repeated sacrifice.'),
  (13, 'From henceforth expecting till his enemies be made his footstool.',
   'τὸ λοιπὸν ἐκδεχόμενος ἕως τεθῶσιν οἱ ἐχθροὶ αὐτοῦ ὑποπόδιον τῶν ποδῶν αὐτοῦ',
   'to loipon ekdechomenos heōs tethōsin hoi echthroi autou hypopodion tōn podōn autou',
   '''From henceforth expecting'' (to loipon ekdechomenos — for the remaining time, waiting). Quoting Psalm 110:1 again. Christ''s session is not passive; He is actively reigning, waiting for the final subjugation of all enemies. His priestly work is complete; His kingly rule continues until every enemy is under His feet. The ''enemies'' include sin, death, Satan, and all opposition to God''s reign.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'For by one offering he hath perfected for ever them that are sanctified.',
   'μιᾷ γὰρ προσφορᾷ τετελείωκεν εἰς τὸ διηνεκὲς τοὺς ἁγιαζομένους',
   'mia gar prosphora teteleiōken eis to diēnekes tous hagiazomenous',
   '''By one offering'' (mia prosphora — by a single offering). ''He hath perfected for ever'' (teteleiōken eis to diēnekes — He has completed/perfected permanently; perfect tense: the perfecting is accomplished and enduring). ''Them that are sanctified'' (tous hagiazomenous — those who are being sanctified; present participle: their sanctification is ongoing in experience). The juxtaposition is deliberate: the perfecting is complete (perfect tense) while the sanctifying is ongoing (present tense). Christ''s one offering has permanently secured the complete salvation of His people, even as they continue to grow in holiness.',
   'This verse is the doctrinal summit of Hebrews'' sacrificial theology. One offering — one! — has perfected forever those who are being sanctified. The perfect tense ''has perfected'' (teteleiōken) means the work is done, finished, complete. The present participle ''being sanctified'' (hagiazomenous) means the experiential outworking continues. Position: perfect. Practice: progressing. Both are secured by the single offering.'),
  (15, 'Whereof the Holy Ghost also is a witness to us: for after that he had said before,',
   'μαρτυρεῖ δὲ ἡμῖν καὶ τὸ πνεῦμα τὸ ἅγιον μετὰ γὰρ τὸ εἰρηκέναι',
   'martyrei de hēmin kai to pneuma to hagion meta gar to eirēkenai',
   'The Holy Spirit is invoked as witness (as in 3:7), confirming the argument from Jeremiah 31. The Spirit''s testimony through Scripture validates the doctrinal conclusion: the new covenant achieves what the old could not.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'This is the covenant that I will make with them after those days, saith the Lord, I will put my laws into their hearts, and in their minds will I write them;',
   'αὕτη ἡ διαθήκη ἣν διαθήσομαι πρὸς αὐτοὺς μετὰ τὰς ἡμέρας ἐκείνας λέγει κύριος διδοὺς νόμους μου ἐπὶ καρδίας αὐτῶν καὶ ἐπὶ τῶν διανοιῶν αὐτῶν ἐπιγράψω αὐτούς',
   'hautē hē diathēkē hēn diathēsomai pros autous meta tas hēmeras ekeinas legei kyrios didous nomous mou epi kardias autōn kai epi tōn dianoiōn autōn epigraphsō autous',
   'Jeremiah 31:33 quoted again (cf. 8:10). The internal writing of God''s law — on hearts and minds — is the hallmark of the new covenant.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'And their sins and iniquities will I remember no more.',
   'καὶ τῶν ἁμαρτιῶν αὐτῶν καὶ τῶν ἀνομιῶν αὐτῶν οὐ μὴ μνησθῶ ἔτι',
   'kai tōn hamartiōn autōn kai tōn anomiōn autōn ou mē mnēsthō eti',
   '''I will remember no more'' (ou mē mnēsthō eti — I will absolutely not remember any longer). This is the climactic promise: complete, final, permanent forgiveness. God''s ''not remembering'' is not forgetfulness but a deliberate, covenantal decision never to hold sins against His people again.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'Now where remission of these is, there is no more offering for sin.',
   'ὅπου δὲ ἄφεσις τούτων οὐκέτι προσφορὰ περὶ ἁμαρτίας',
   'hopou de aphesis toutōn ouketi prosphora peri hamartias',
   '''Where remission of these is'' (hopou aphesis toutōn — where there is forgiveness of these sins). ''No more offering for sin'' (ouketi prosphora peri hamartias — no longer any offering concerning sin). This is the logical conclusion of the entire doctrinal argument: if sins are fully forgiven (as Jeremiah 31 promises), then no further sacrifice is needed. The sacrificial system is not just superseded but rendered unnecessary. This single verse demolishes every system — whether Jewish or Christian — that requires ongoing sacrifice for sin. The work is done.',
   'This verse is the formal conclusion of Hebrews'' doctrinal argument (chs.1-10:18). If forgiveness is complete (Jer 31:34), no more offering is needed. The entire sacrificial system — Levitical and otherwise — is rendered obsolete by the completeness of Christ''s work. From this point forward, the epistle moves to application: how should we then live?'),
  (19, 'Having therefore, brethren, boldness to enter into the holiest by the blood of Jesus,',
   'ἔχοντες οὖν ἀδελφοί παρρησίαν εἰς τὴν εἴσοδον τῶν ἁγίων ἐν τῷ αἵματι Ἰησοῦ',
   'echontes oun adelphoi parrēsian eis tēn eisodon tōn hagiōn en tō haimati Iēsou',
   '''Having therefore'' (echontes oun — since we have; drawing the practical conclusion from the doctrinal argument). ''Boldness'' (parrēsian — confidence, freedom of speech, open access; the word from 3:6 and 4:16). ''To enter into the holiest'' (eis tēn eisodon tōn hagiōn — entrance into the holy places/Holy of Holies). ''By the blood of Jesus'' — the ground of our access. What was forbidden under the old covenant (only one priest, one day per year) is now the privilege of every believer: direct, bold, confident access to God''s presence.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'By a new and living way, which he hath consecrated for us, through the veil, that is to say, his flesh;',
   'ἣν ἐνεκαίνισεν ἡμῖν ὁδὸν πρόσφατον καὶ ζῶσαν διὰ τοῦ καταπετάσματος τοῦτ᾽ ἔστιν τῆς σαρκὸς αὐτοῦ',
   'hēn enekainisen hēmin hodon prosphaton kai zōsan dia tou katapetasmatos tout estin tēs sarkos autou',
   '''New'' (prosphaton — freshly killed, recently slaughtered; originally used of a freshly slain sacrifice, then ''new/fresh'' in general). ''Living'' (zōsan — alive). The way into God''s presence is both new (prosphaton) and living (zōsan) — not an old, dead ritual but a fresh, living pathway. ''Through the veil, that is to say, his flesh'' — Christ''s body is the veil. When His flesh was torn on the cross, the veil of the temple was torn (Matt 27:51), opening the way into God''s presence. His broken body is the door through which we enter.',
   'The identification of Christ''s flesh with the temple veil is one of Hebrews'' most striking images. The veil that once barred access now, torn open, is the very means of access. Christ''s death — the tearing of His flesh — opened the way that His life, as the veil, had symbolically closed. The way to God goes through the cross.'),
  (21, 'And having an high priest over the house of God;',
   'καὶ ἱερέα μέγαν ἐπὶ τὸν οἶκον τοῦ θεοῦ',
   'kai hierea megan epi ton oikon tou theou',
   '''A great priest'' (hierea megan — a priest who is great; echoing 4:14). ''Over the house of God'' (epi ton oikon tou theou — over God''s household; cf. 3:6). Two grounds for confidence: (1) the blood of Jesus opens the way (vv.19-20); (2) a great priest presides over God''s house. Both are needed: access and advocacy, the way opened and the priest interceding.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'Let us draw near with a true heart in full assurance of faith, having our hearts sprinkled from an evil conscience, and our bodies washed with pure water.',
   'προσερχώμεθα μετὰ ἀληθινῆς καρδίας ἐν πληροφορίᾳ πίστεως ἐρραντισμένοι τὰς καρδίας ἀπὸ συνειδήσεως πονηρᾶς καὶ λελουμένοι τὸ σῶμα ὕδατι καθαρῷ',
   'proserchōmetha meta alēthinēs kardias en plērophoria pisteōs errantismenoi tas kardias apo syneidēseōs ponēras kai leloumenoi to sōma hydati katharō',
   'The first of three great exhortations (''let us''). ''Draw near'' (proserchōmetha — let us approach; the word for approaching God, the priestly term for coming to the altar). ''True heart'' (alēthinēs kardias — a genuine, sincere heart). ''Full assurance of faith'' (plērophoria pisteōs — complete conviction of faith). ''Hearts sprinkled from an evil conscience'' — alluding to the sprinkling of blood on the Day of Atonement; Christ''s blood has cleansed the inner person. ''Bodies washed with pure water'' — likely alluding to baptism, the outward sign of inward cleansing. Interior and exterior, heart and body, are both addressed.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'Let us hold fast the profession of our faith without wavering; (for he is faithful that promised;)',
   'κατέχωμεν τὴν ὁμολογίαν τῆς ἐλπίδος ἀκλινῆ πιστὸς γὰρ ὁ ἐπαγγειλάμενος',
   'katechōmen tēn homologian tēs elpidos aklinē pistos gar ho epangeilamenos',
   'The second exhortation. ''Hold fast'' (katechōmen — let us grip firmly, retain tenaciously). ''The profession of our faith/hope'' (tēn homologian tēs elpidos — the confession of our hope). ''Without wavering'' (aklinē — unbending, without leaning, without inclination to either side). ''For he is faithful that promised'' (pistos ho epangeilamenos — the one who promised is faithful). The ground of perseverance is not our grip but God''s faithfulness — we hold fast because He holds firm.',
   NULL),
  (24, 'And let us consider one another to provoke unto love and to good works:',
   'καὶ κατανοῶμεν ἀλλήλους εἰς παροξυσμὸν ἀγάπης καὶ καλῶν ἔργων',
   'kai katanoōmen allēlous eis paroxysmon agapēs kai kalōn ergōn',
   'The third exhortation. ''Consider one another'' (katanoōmen allēlous — observe one another carefully; the same intensive katanoeō from 3:1). ''Provoke'' (paroxysmon — stimulation, incitement, sharp encouragement; the word can mean irritation [Acts 15:39] but here means positive prodding). ''Unto love and good works'' — the goal is not irritation but inspiration. Believers are to study one another so as to spur one another toward love and action.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'Not forsaking the assembling of ourselves together, as the manner of some is; but exhorting one another: and so much the more, as ye see the day approaching.',
   'μὴ ἐγκαταλείποντες τὴν ἐπισυναγωγὴν ἑαυτῶν καθὼς ἔθος τισίν ἀλλὰ παρακαλοῦντες καὶ τοσούτῳ μᾶλλον ὅσῳ βλέπετε ἐγγίζουσαν τὴν ἡμέραν',
   'mē enkataleipontes tēn episynagōgēn heautōn kathōs ethos tisin alla parakalountes kai tosoutō mallon hosō blepete engizyousan tēn hēmeran',
   '''Not forsaking'' (mē enkataleipontes — not abandoning, not deserting). ''The assembling'' (tēn episynagōgēn — the gathering together; from epi + synagōgē). ''As the manner of some is'' (kathōs ethos tisin — as is the habit/custom of some). ''The day approaching'' (engizyousan tēn hēmeran — the day drawing near, coming closer). Isolation is dangerous; community is protective. As ''the day'' (the return of Christ, the final judgment) approaches, gathering becomes more urgent, not less.',
   'This verse establishes the necessity of regular Christian assembly. The command is grounded in the approaching Day of the Lord — as the end draws near, believers need each other more, not less. Forsaking the assembly (which some were already doing) leaves believers vulnerable to the drift, hardening, and apostasy warned against throughout the epistle.'),
  (26, 'For if we sin wilfully after that we have received the knowledge of the truth, there remaineth no more sacrifice for sins,',
   'ἑκουσίως γὰρ ἁμαρτανόντων ἡμῶν μετὰ τὸ λαβεῖν τὴν ἐπίγνωσιν τῆς ἀληθείας οὐκέτι περὶ ἁμαρτιῶν ἀπολείπεται θυσία',
   'hekousiōs gar hamartanontōn hēmōn meta to labein tēn epignōsin tēs alētheias ouketi peri hamartiōn apoleipetai thysia',
   '''Wilfully'' (hekousiōs — voluntarily, deliberately, intentionally; as opposed to sins of ignorance). ''After that we have received the knowledge of the truth'' (meta to labein tēn epignōsin tēs alētheias — after receiving full knowledge; epignōsis is full, thorough knowledge, not casual acquaintance). ''No more sacrifice for sins'' (ouketi peri hamartiōn apoleipetai thysia — no longer is there a sacrifice left for sins). This is the fourth warning passage. The ''wilful sin'' in context is not any deliberate sin but apostasy — the deliberate, knowing rejection of Christ''s sacrifice after having fully understood it. Since Christ''s is the only sacrifice for sin (there is no Plan B), rejecting it leaves nothing.',
   'This is the fourth and most severe warning passage (cf. 6:4-6). The ''wilful sin'' is apostasy: the deliberate rejection of Christ after full knowledge. The logic is: if Christ''s sacrifice is the only sacrifice for sins (vv.1-18), then rejecting it leaves no other means of atonement. This is not describing a believer who struggles with sin but someone who knowingly, deliberately abandons the faith.'),
  (27, 'But a certain fearful looking for of judgment and fiery indignation, which shall devour the adversaries.',
   'φοβερὰ δέ τις ἐκδοχὴ κρίσεως καὶ πυρὸς ζῆλος ἐσθίειν μέλλοντος τοὺς ὑπεναντίους',
   'phobera de tis ekdochē kriseōs kai pyros zēlos esthiein mellontos tous hypenantious',
   '''Fearful'' (phobera — terrifying, dreadful). ''Looking for'' (ekdochē — expectation, anticipation). ''Judgment'' (kriseōs). ''Fiery indignation'' (pyros zēlos — fire of zeal/jealousy; cf. Deut 4:24, ''the LORD thy God is a consuming fire''). ''Devour the adversaries'' (esthiein mellontos tous hypenantious — about to consume those who are hostile). For those who reject Christ, only judgment remains — the unshielded fury of a holy God against sin.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'He that despised Moses'' law died without mercy under two or three witnesses:',
   'ἀθετήσας τις νόμον Μωϋσέως χωρὶς οἰκτιρμῶν ἐπὶ δυσὶν ἢ τρισὶν μάρτυσιν ἀποθνῄσκει',
   'athetēsas tis nomon Mōyseōs chōris oiktirmōn epi dysin ē trisin martysin apothnēskei',
   'The a fortiori argument again: rejecting Moses'' law brought death ''without mercy'' (chōris oiktirmōn — without compassion; the punishment was execution, Deut 17:2-6). If that was the penalty for rejecting the lesser covenant, how much worse for rejecting the greater?',
   NULL),
  (29, 'Of how much sorer punishment, suppose ye, shall he be thought worthy, who hath trodden under foot the Son of God, and hath counted the blood of the covenant, wherewith he was sanctified, an unholy thing, and hath done despite unto the Spirit of grace?',
   'πόσῳ δοκεῖτε χείρονος ἀξιωθήσεται τιμωρίας ὁ τὸν υἱὸν τοῦ θεοῦ καταπατήσας καὶ τὸ αἷμα τῆς διαθήκης κοινὸν ἡγησάμενος ἐν ᾧ ἡγιάσθη καὶ τὸ πνεῦμα τῆς χάριτος ἐνυβρίσας',
   'posō dokeite cheironos axiōthēsetai timōrias ho ton hyion tou theou katapatēsas kai to haima tēs diathēkēs koinon hēgēsamenos en hō hēgiasthē kai to pneuma tēs charitos enybristas',
   '''How much sorer punishment'' (posō cheironos timōrias — how much worse punishment). Three descriptions of apostasy as three offenses against the three persons of the Trinity: (1) ''Trodden under foot the Son of God'' (ton hyion tou theou katapatēsas — trampling the Son of God; treating Him as worthless, as dirt to be walked on). (2) ''Counted the blood of the covenant … an unholy thing'' (to haima tēs diathēkēs koinon hēgēsamenos — regarding the covenant blood as common, profane, unclean; koinon means ordinary, not set apart). ''Wherewith he was sanctified'' (en hō hēgiasthē — by which he was set apart; suggesting the apostate once participated in covenant blessings). (3) ''Done despite unto the Spirit of grace'' (to pneuma tēs charitos enybristas — insulting, outraging the Spirit of grace; enybrizō means to insult with arrogance and contempt).',
   'This verse describes apostasy as a threefold offense against the Trinity: trampling the Son, profaning the blood, and insulting the Spirit. The trinitarian structure mirrors the trinitarian benediction of 2 Cor 13:14 but in negative: the apostate rejects the grace of the Son, the love of the Father (expressed in the covenant), and the communion of the Spirit. No greater crime is conceivable.'),
  (30, 'For we know him that hath said, Vengeance belongeth unto me, I will recompense, saith the Lord. And again, The Lord shall judge his people.',
   'οἴδαμεν γὰρ τὸν εἰπόντα ἐμοὶ ἐκδίκησις ἐγὼ ἀνταποδώσω λέγει κύριος καὶ πάλιν κύριος κρινεῖ τὸν λαὸν αὐτοῦ',
   'oidamen gar ton eiponta emoi ekdikēsis egō antapodōsō legei kyrios kai palin kyrios krinei ton laon autou',
   'Two OT quotations: (1) Deuteronomy 32:35 — ''Vengeance is mine, I will repay.'' (2) Deuteronomy 32:36 — ''The LORD shall judge his people.'' The sobering truth: God will judge not just pagan enemies but ''his people'' — those within the covenant community. Judgment begins at the house of God (1 Pet 4:17). The God of mercy is also the God of justice.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God.',
   'φοβερὸν τὸ ἐμπεσεῖν εἰς χεῖρας θεοῦ ζῶντος',
   'phoberon to empesein eis cheiras theou zōntos',
   '''Fearful'' (phoberon — terrifying, dreadful; the same word as v.27). ''To fall into the hands'' (empesein eis cheiras — to fall into the grasp of). ''The living God'' (theou zōntos — not a dead idol but the living, active, responding God). For the unbelieving and apostate, God''s ''living'' nature is not comfort but terror — He is alive, active, aware, and will act. The same ''living God'' who gives life to the faithful (3:12) is the terror of the unfaithful.',
   'This verse, one of the most terrifying in Scripture, is the complement of 4:16 (the throne of grace). For those who come through Christ, God''s presence is grace; for those who reject Christ, God''s presence is judgment. The same God, the same throne, but the approach determines everything.'),
  (32, 'But call to remembrance the former days, in which, after ye were illuminated, ye endured a great fight of afflictions;',
   'ἀναμιμνήσκεσθε δὲ τὰς πρότερον ἡμέρας ἐν αἷς φωτισθέντες πολλὴν ἄθλησιν ὑπεμείνατε παθημάτων',
   'anamimnēskesthe de tas proteron hēmeras en hais phōtisthentes pollēn athlēsin hypemeinate pathēmatōn',
   '''Call to remembrance'' (anamimnēskesthe — recall, remember; the author shifts from warning to encouragement). ''After ye were illuminated'' (phōtisthentes — after being enlightened; cf. 6:4). ''A great fight of afflictions'' (pollēn athlēsin pathēmatōn — a great athletic contest of sufferings; athlēsis is the word from which ''athletics'' derives). The readers had already endured severe persecution after their conversion — they are not untested. The author appeals to their history of faithfulness as motivation for continued perseverance.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'Partly, whilst ye were made a gazingstock both by reproaches and afflictions; and partly, whilst ye became companions of them that were so used.',
   'τοῦτο μὲν ὀνειδισμοῖς τε καὶ θλίψεσιν θεατριζόμενοι τοῦτο δὲ κοινωνοὶ τῶν οὕτως ἀναστρεφομένων γενηθέντες',
   'touto men oneidismois te kai thlipsesin theatrizomenoi touto de koinōnoi tōn houtōs anastrephomenōn genēthentes',
   '''Gazingstock'' (theatrizomenoi — publicly exposed, made a spectacle; from theatron, theater). ''Reproaches'' (oneidismois — insults, verbal abuse). ''Afflictions'' (thlipsesin — pressures, tribulations). ''Companions'' (koinōnoi — sharers, partners). They endured both direct persecution and solidarity with persecuted brothers — they did not abandon those who suffered but identified with them.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'For ye had compassion of me in my bonds, and took joyfully the spoiling of your goods, knowing in yourselves that ye have in heaven a better and an enduring substance.',
   'καὶ γὰρ τοῖς δεσμοῖς μου συνεπαθήσατε καὶ τὴν ἁρπαγὴν τῶν ὑπαρχόντων ὑμῶν μετὰ χαρᾶς προσεδέξασθε γινώσκοντες ἔχειν ἑαυτοὺς κρείττονα ὕπαρξιν ἐν οὐρανοῖς καὶ μένουσαν',
   'kai gar tois desmois mou synepathēsate kai tēn harpagēn tōn hyparchontōn hymōn meta charas prosedexasthe ginōskontes echein heautous kreittona hyparxin en ouranois kai menousan',
   '''Compassion of me in my bonds'' (tois desmois mou synepathēsate — you sympathized with my imprisonment). ''Took joyfully the spoiling of your goods'' (tēn harpagēn tōn hyparchontōn hymōn meta charas prosedexasthe — you accepted with joy the plundering of your possessions). ''Knowing … a better and enduring substance'' (kreittona hyparxin en ouranois kai menousan — a better and permanent possession in heaven). They could endure the loss of earthly goods because they knew they had heavenly treasure that could never be taken. This is the faith that enables perseverance.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'Cast not away therefore your confidence, which hath great recompence of reward.',
   'μὴ ἀποβάλητε οὖν τὴν παρρησίαν ὑμῶν ἥτις ἔχει μεγάλην μισθαποδοσίαν',
   'mē apobalēte oun tēn parrēsian hymōn hētis echei megalēn misthapodosian',
   '''Cast not away'' (mē apobalēte — do not throw away, do not discard). ''Your confidence'' (tēn parrēsian hymōn — your boldness; the same parrēsia that characterizes faithful believers throughout Hebrews). ''Great recompence of reward'' (megalēn misthapodosian — a great repayment, a magnificent return). The confidence they have demonstrated is not to be abandoned — it carries the promise of divine reward. Perseverance has a payoff; faithfulness will be rewarded.',
   NULL),
  (36, 'For ye have need of patience, that, after ye have done the will of God, ye might receive the promise.',
   'ὑπομονῆς γὰρ ἔχετε χρείαν ἵνα τὸ θέλημα τοῦ θεοῦ ποιήσαντες κομίσησθε τὴν ἐπαγγελίαν',
   'hypomonēs gar echete chreian hina to thelēma tou theou poiēsantes komisēsthe tēn epangelian',
   '''Patience'' (hypomonēs — endurance, perseverance, steadfast endurance under pressure; from hypo + menō, to remain under). ''After ye have done the will of God'' — the promise is received after endurance, not immediately. ''Receive the promise'' (komisēsthe tēn epangelian — to carry off, to obtain the promise). The structure is: do God''s will → endure → receive the promise. There is a gap between doing and receiving — and that gap is filled by patience.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'For yet a little while, and he that shall come will come, and will not tarry.',
   'ἔτι γὰρ μικρὸν ὅσον ὅσον ὁ ἐρχόμενος ἥξει καὶ οὐ χρονιεῖ',
   'eti gar mikron hoson hoson ho erchomenos hēxei kai ou chroniei',
   'Quoting Isaiah 26:20 and Habakkuk 2:3 (LXX). ''A little while'' (mikron hoson hoson — a very, very little while; the doubled hoson intensifies the brevity). ''He that shall come will come'' (ho erchomenos hēxei — the Coming One will arrive). ''Will not tarry'' (ou chroniei — will not delay). The wait for Christ''s return may feel long, but in God''s timeline it is ''a little while.'' This promise sustains endurance: the delay is temporary; the coming is certain.',
   NULL),
  (38, 'Now the just shall live by faith: but if any man draw back, my soul shall have no pleasure in him.',
   'ὁ δὲ δίκαιος ἐκ πίστεως ζήσεται καὶ ἐὰν ὑποστείληται οὐκ εὐδοκεῖ ἡ ψυχή μου ἐν αὐτῷ',
   'ho de dikaios ek pisteōs zēsetai kai ean hyposteilētai ouk eudokei hē psychē mou en autō',
   '''The just shall live by faith'' (ho dikaios ek pisteōs zēsetai — Habakkuk 2:4; the same text Paul quotes in Rom 1:17 and Gal 3:11). This is the bridge to chapter 11 — the great ''faith chapter.'' ''If any man draw back'' (ean hyposteilētai — if he shrinks back, if he retreats). ''My soul shall have no pleasure in him'' (ouk eudokei hē psychē mou — my soul is not pleased). Two paths: faith that perseveres, or shrinking back that displeases God. The warning is against the latter; the encouragement is toward the former.',
   'Habakkuk 2:4 — ''the just shall live by faith'' — is one of the most important OT texts in the NT. Paul uses it to establish justification by faith (Rom 1:17; Gal 3:11). Hebrews uses it to establish perseverance by faith. Both are correct: the same faith that justifies also sustains — faith is not a one-time act but an ongoing way of life.'),
  (39, 'But we are not of them who draw back unto perdition; but of them that believe to the saving of the soul.',
   'ἡμεῖς δὲ οὐκ ἐσμὲν ὑποστολῆς εἰς ἀπώλειαν ἀλλὰ πίστεως εἰς περιποίησιν ψυχῆς',
   'hēmeis de ouk esmen hypostolēs eis apōleian alla pisteōs eis peripoiēsin psychēs',
   '''We are not of them who draw back'' (ouk esmen hypostolēs — we are not of shrinking back; the genitive suggests character: we do not belong to the category of those who retreat). ''Unto perdition'' (eis apōleian — unto destruction, ruin, eternal loss). ''But of them that believe'' (alla pisteōs — but of faith). ''To the saving of the soul'' (eis peripoiēsin psychēs — unto the preservation/possession of the soul). As in 6:9, the author expresses confidence in his readers: they are not headed for apostasy but for salvation. The verse is the perfect transition to chapter 11: from warning about faithlessness to the celebration of faith.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews' AND c.chapter_number = 10;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.word_order
FROM verses v
JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  ('ἀνάμνησις', 'anamnēsis', 'G364', 'Remembrance, recollection, memorial — from ana (again) + mimnēskō (to remember). In v.3 the annual Day of Atonement served as an anamnēsis of sins — not a forgetting but a remembering. The old covenant sacrifices reminded worshippers of their sin rather than removing it. Contrast this with the Lord''s Supper (Luke 22:19), which is an anamnēsis of Christ''s completed sacrifice — a joyful remembrance of forgiveness accomplished, not a painful reminder of sins unforgiven.', 1),
  ('πρόσφατος', 'prosphatos', 'G4372', 'New, fresh, recently made — originally ''freshly slain/slaughtered'' (from pros + sphazo, to slay). In v.20 the way to God through Christ is prosphatos — fresh, newly opened, not stale or outdated. Unlike the old covenant path (ancient, worn, and now obsolete), the way through Christ''s flesh is perpetually fresh — as new and vital today as when it was first opened at the cross. A NT hapax in its adjectival form.', 2),
  ('ἐπισυναγωγή', 'episynagōgē', 'G1997', 'Assembling together, gathering, congregation — from epi (together) + synagōgē (assembly). In v.25 believers are not to forsake their episynagōgē — their regular gathering together. The word emphasizes the coming together of scattered individuals into one body. The prefix epi intensifies the gathering: a deliberate, purposeful assembling. Used only here and in 2 Thessalonians 2:1 (of the gathering to Christ at His coming).', 3),
  ('ἑκουσίως', 'hekousiōs', 'G1596', 'Willingly, voluntarily, deliberately — from hekōn (willing). In v.26 the ''wilful'' sin is deliberate, informed, conscious apostasy — not a momentary lapse but a calculated rejection of known truth. The word emphasizes personal agency and full awareness. The apostate does not stumble accidentally but walks away deliberately, with full knowledge of what they are rejecting and what they are choosing instead.', 4),
  ('καταπατέω', 'katapateō', 'G2662', 'To trample underfoot, to tread upon, to treat with contempt — from kata (down) + pateō (to tread). In v.29 the apostate ''tramples'' the Son of God — treats Him as dirt to be walked on, as worthless refuse. The image is deliberately shocking: the Son of God, the Creator of the universe, treated as garbage beneath the feet. This is the ultimate expression of contempt for divine grace.', 5),
  ('ὑπομονή', 'hypomonē', 'G5281', 'Endurance, patience, steadfast perseverance under pressure — from hypo (under) + menō (to remain). In v.36 believers ''have need of patience'' — not passive resignation but active, resolute endurance that holds firm under pressure. Hypomonē is the virtue that bridges the gap between promise and fulfillment, between doing God''s will and receiving God''s reward. It is the characteristic virtue of faith in action over time.', 6)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Hebrews' AND c.chapter_number = 10
  AND v.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
    WHEN 1 THEN 3
    WHEN 2 THEN 20
    WHEN 3 THEN 25
    WHEN 4 THEN 26
    WHEN 5 THEN 29
    WHEN 6 THEN 36
  END;

